<LP>
   NEW ORDERS for durable goods plummeted 10.5% in November,
matching January's record fall and offering further evidence
of a steep economic downturn in the fourth quarter. Excluding
transportation orders, the decline was 3.5%. Orders for
nondefense goods were down 16.4%.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Consumer confidence remained virtually unchanged this
month from November but is much lower than a year ago, a
survey reported. Separately, help-wanted advertising reached
a five-year low in November.
   ---
   Stock prices slipped on the weak durable-goods report, but
bonds rose on the news. The Dow Jones Industrial Average
declined 11.63 points to close at 2625.50. The 30-year
Treasury bond gained almost half a point.
                                                                                                       

   An electrical explosion shut down the Big Board for 1 1/2
hours, prompting the SEC to order a trading halt at all U.S.
exchanges. But some brokers and institutions bypassed the
exchanges and continued to trade.
   ---
   Retail gasoline prices plunged an average of nearly nine
cents a gallon in the past week, and could fall more. The
decline at the pump follows a recent drop in wholesale
prices.
   ---
   First Executive agreed not to write new insurance policies
in New Jersey rather than pay a $500 million security deposit
the state demanded.
   ---
   TWA owner Carl Icahn is preparing to make the ouster of
Pan Am Chairman Thomas Plaskett a condition for a purchase of
Pan Am by TWA, people close to their talks say.
   ---
   AMR's American Airlines won a court order barring its
pilots union from engaging in a sickout or other work
slowdowns. The union denied it is conducting such a job
action.
   ---
   Contracts for new construction reached their lowest level
in five years in November. Nonresidential building contracts
declined 8%, while new-home start-ups were off 4%.
   ---
   Most stock funds performed worse than the S&amp;P 500 this
year for the eighth straight year, despite the benefit of
holding cash in a bear market. The average fund's total
return is a negative 6.8% so far this year.
   ---
   Private foreign investors sold $1.5 billion more U.S.
stocks and bonds than they bought in the third quarter.
   ---
   Georgia-Pacific and International Paper were named in a $2
billion law suit alleging the companies dumped dioxin into
three rivers in Mississippi.
   ---
   The Senate's banking chief asked the Treasury to launch a
wide-ranging study of insurance companies amid growing
congressional concern.
   ---
   Procter &amp; Gamble created an Eastern European division to
oversee its sales operations in the region.
   ---
   Taiwan's cabinet approved regulations opening the Taipei
stock market to direct investment of as much as $2.5 billion
by foreign institutions.
   ---
   Tokyo stocks ended little changed Thursday after
profit-taking late in the session. London shares rose.
